<h1>To Lund Washington</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Dear Lund,</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">New York May 10th 1776.</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>As I am not able to form any Idea of the time of my return, and as it is very reasonable and just that Mr Custis should be possessed of his Estate, although it is not in my power (circumstanced as I am at present) to Liquidate the Accounts and make a final settlement with him, I have wrote to the Clerk of the Secretarys Office for Authentic Copies of the last Accounts which I exhibited against him and the Estate of his deceased Sister.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> With these (for I have directed them to be sent to you) and the bundle of Bonds which you will find among my Papers, I would have Mr Custis and you repair to Colonel Mason, and get him, as a common friend to us both, as a Gentleman well acquainted with business and very capable of drawing up a proper Memorandum of the transaction, to deliver him his own Bonds, which, if my memory fails me not, and no changes have happened, are in one parcel and indorsed; and at the same time deliver him as many Bonds out of the other parcel, endorsed Miss Custiss Bonds, as will pay him his Moiety of her Fortune, and the Balance which will appear due to him from me, at my last settlement with General Court. How the acct will then stand between us, I cannot, with precision, say, but believe the Balance will be rather in my favour than his.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
<p>In my last settlement of the Estate of Miss Custis (which you will have sent to you, I expect, by Mr Everard) every Bond, Mortgage, &amp;c. were fully accounted for and will be the best Ground to found the dividend (between Mr Custis and myself)
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-04-02-pb-0272">[272]</span>
upon, lest any of the Bonds or Mortgages should be misplaced, or in the Office.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0003" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0003-ptr">3</a></p>
<p>Mr Mercers Bonds I have promised to take into my part; and as there are Wheat and other Accounts opened between that Estate and me, I should be glad to have them allotted accordingly. In like manner, I promised to take Mr Robert Adamss debt upon myself and believe the last Mortgage from him was taken in my own name.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0004" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> As to the others, I do not care how they are divided, nor was I anxious about these, further than that it served to comply with their desires, founded (I believe) on an Opinion, that I should not press them for the money.</p>
<p>The Bank stock must, I presume, be equally divided between us. Long before I left Virginia, I directed it to be sold, writing to Messieurs Cary and Co., who had always received the dividends, to negotiate the matter: In consequence they sent me a power of Attorney, and a great deal of formal stuff for Mrs Washington and myself to execute before the Governor. This we did, literally as required, and transmitted; since which the Directors of the Bank have prescribed another Mode, and I have had forwarded to me another set of Papers to be executed also before the Governor, which has never been in my power to do, as they arrived but a little while before I set out for the Congress last Spring. Thus the matter stands, as far as I know, with respect to the money in the Funds.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0005" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0005-ptr">5</a></p>
<p>There is another matter, which I think justice to myself requires a mention of, and that is with respect to the Sterling Balance which it will appear I was owing Mr Custis upon last settlement. It was then, and ever since has been, my intention to assign him, as many Bonds, carrying Interest, as would discharge this Ballance, but my attendance upon Congress in the Fall 1774, and Spring 1775, put it out of my power to attend the General Courts at this Sessions; consequently no Order could be taken, or account rendered, of this matter; and now, by the rise of exchange, if I was to turn Current Money Bonds into Sterling, I should be a considerable sufferer, when I had not, nor could have, any interest in delaying of it; and that it was so delayed, was owing to the Reasons abovementioned, it being a practice to let out his Money upon Interest, as soon as it came to my Hands.</p>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-04-02-pb-0273">[273]</span>
<p>The many matters, which hang heavy upon my hands at present, do not allow me time to add, but oblige me to request, as I have not wrote fully to Colonel Mason on this subject, that you will shew him, and, if necessary, let him have this Letter.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0006" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0006-ptr">6</a> I am very sincerely, Your Affectionate, humble servant,</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">G. Washington</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0213-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>GWs letter to Thomas Everard, clerk of the secretary to the Virginia General Court, on this subject has not been found.</p>


   <p>GW submitted his accounts for his guardianship of the Custis childrens estate to the General Court for approval every two years. The last accounts were submitted in 1773, the year of John Parke Custiss marriage and Martha Parke Custiss death. See Settlement of the Daniel Parke Custis Estate, 20 April 17595 November 1761, and Washingtons Guardianship of the Custis Heirs, 21 October 17613 November 1773, printed in vol. 6 and vol. 7, respectively, of the <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ W. W. Abbot et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;The Papers of George Washington, Colonial Series&lt;/i&gt;. 10 vols. Charlottesville, Va., 198395. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Papers, Colonial Series</span></span>. The guardian accounts for John Parke Custis and Martha Parke Custis go through April 1773, but GW added to Patsys account an entry dated 19 June 1773 (the day of her death) for 206 current money as a balance due from Geo. Washington. Both final guardian accounts were settled before the General Court on 3 Nov. 1773. GW listed at the end of each account the money due each child from bonds, Bank of England stock, and other sources. Below this he shows the division of Patsys estate with 2,366.0.2 sterling and 5,183.4.5  current money going to her brother and the same amount to GW (ViLxW: Washingtons Account Book).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>John Parke Custiss account contains the following signed statement by George Mason, dated 28 June 1778: At the Mutual Request of His Excy Genl Washington &amp; John Parke Custis Esqr. I have Settled this Accot between them &amp; Aloted to Mr Custis the Bonds with which he is charged <img class="char" src="images/char-per-trans.png" alt="[per]"/> Contra: leaving the Stock in the Bank of England &amp; the Money in the Hands of Robt Cary Esqr. Mercht of Londn to be divided between them hereafter, as the Transferring the one, or Drawing for the other may be attended with Risque or Difficulty in the Present Situation of America. On the same day John Parke Custis signed a receipt to Lund Washington on account of GW for 160.9.4  current money to balance the account (Ledger B, 216).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-04-02-0213&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0001#GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0001" class="document">note 1</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>Martha Parke Custis at the time of her death held bonds from John Mercer, now deceased, for 2,100 and from his son James Mercer for 1,109.11.6 current money. The Alexandria merchant Robert Adams debt was 1,000 secured by a mortgage to Martha Parke Custis in 1771 on several tracts of land near Leesburg in Loudoun County. In 1774 after Patsys death, the mortgage was renewed in GWs own name (GWs Guardian Accounts, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Virginia Historical Society, Richmond ]">ViHi</span>: Custis Papers; deed from Adam to Martha Parke Custis, 12 Dec. 1771, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Virginia Historical Society, Richmond ]">ViHi</span>: Custis Papers; deed from Adam to GW, 19 Dec. 1774, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Loudoun County Courthouse, Leesburg, Va. [[former abbreviation: ViLoCt]] ]">ViLeeLCh</span>).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>The bank stock was not transferred until after the Revolution. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-01-02-0007" class="document">GW
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-04-02-pb-0274">[274]</span>
to John Parke Custis, 19 June 1775</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-04-02-02-0013" class="document">GW to Wakelin Welch, 27 July 1784</a>, bond from GW, Peyton Randolph, and Robert Carter to the Archbishop of Canterbury, 31 May 1774, and power of administration from the Archbishop of Canterbury to Martha Washington, 16 July 1774, both in <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC</span>: Washington Family Papers.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0213-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>Although George Mason settled GWs account with John Parke Custis at this time, the settlement turned out to be incomplete. Mason neglected to include some late charges on the estate. See GW to Bartholomew Dandridge, 20 April 1782, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>, and Ledger B, 217.</p>

</div>
